Raw dev notes -- Feb-March 2026

I've been building knowledge bases for two different projects -- large collections of
documents that get fed into an AI platform so users can ask questions and get accurate,
sourced answers. The classic RAG (Retrieval-Augmented Generation) setup. But here's
what nobody tells you about RAG: the hardest part isn't the retrieval or the generation.
It's the data preparation. Garbage in, garbage out.

The source documents I was working with were a mess. Scanned PDFs with OCR artifacts,
inconsistent formatting, tables that didn't survive format conversion, duplicate content
across files, irrelevant boilerplate sections. If you feed this raw into a knowledge
base, the AI's answers are mediocre at best.

So I built an LLM-powered cleanup pipeline. The idea: run every document through Gemini
to clean up OCR errors, standardize formatting, and remove noise -- but with strict
guardrails to prevent the AI from changing meaning or adding information.

The pipeline:
1. Standardize formats: PDF, DOCX, HTML all get converted to clean Markdown
2. Assess RAG-readiness: score each document and flag problems
3. Detect overlap: find duplicate or near-duplicate content across files
4. LLM cleanup via Gemini with async concurrent chunk processing (for speed)
5. Quality gate: reject any chunk where output exceeds 105% of input length
6. Batch into upload-sized packages with proper heading separators

That 105% quality gate was the most important decision. Without it, the LLM would
helpfully 'improve' the text by paraphrasing and expanding -- exactly what you don't
want when preparing reference material. I also had to explicitly tell the model NOT
to reconstruct mathematical formulas, because it kept 'fixing' math notation that was
actually correct in its original form.

I also built a benchmark to compare different AI platforms on Hebrew-language questions
with ground-truth answers. The differences in Hebrew handling were surprising -- some
platforms clearly invested more in multilingual support than others.

Technical gotcha that cost me hours: when processing multiple files sequentially with
async code, you have to reset the Google SDK client between event loop runs. Otherwise
you get obscure connection pool errors that look like network issues.

At the end of this phase, I archived 75 one-off scripts that had accumulated during
development. The cleanup was satisfying -- reducing a messy root directory to just
the pipeline scripts and docs.

This whole project reinforced my belief that AI-assisted workflows aren't about
having a smart model. They're about building the right pipeline around the model --
validation, quality gates, fallbacks, monitoring. The AI is just one step.
